Kolon Industries, Shinhan, SM, Security Bank: Asia Ex-Japan Equity Preview

-- B y   A n u c h i t   N g u y e n
-- 
2011-02-14T20:40:07Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-14/kolon-shinhan-sm-security-bank-asia-ex-japan-equity-preview.html
The following companies may have
unusual price changes in Asian trading, excluding Japan. Stock
symbols are in parentheses, and share prices are from the
previous close, unless noted otherwise.  Kolon Industries Co. (120110 KS): The South Korean textile
maker plans to buy the shares in subsidiary Cambridge Kolon Co.
on the market that it doesn’t own. Cambridge Kolon owners will
get 782,580 shares of the merged company, or 0.16 share for
every one of the existing securities, on May 16, Kolon said in a
regulatory filing. Kolon gained 2.9 percent to 75,000 won.  Shinhan Financial Group Co. (055550 KS):  South Korea ’s
largest financial services group plans to bid for Samhwa Mutual
Savings Bank as soon as the company is put up for sale,
according to a regulatory filing. Shinhan gained 2.3 percent to
49,800 won.    SM Prime Holdings Inc . (SMPH PM): The Philippines’ largest
mall operator said its 2010 net income rose 12 percent to 7.9
billion pesos ($180.6 million).  Revenue rose 16 percent to 23.7
billion pesos, the company said in a regulatory filing. SM Prime
said it plans to open three new malls this year to bring its
total to 47 malls in the  Philippines  and in  China . The stock
increased 2.9 percent to 10.70 pesos.    Security Bank Corp . (SECB PM): The Philippine lender said
profit rose 134 percent to 7.2 billion pesos last year, the
lender said without providing a comparative figure. Revenue
increased 63 percent to 12.9 billion pesos, boosted by trading
gains, Security Bank said in a disclosure to the stock exchange.
Security Bank dropped 1.1 percent to 80.40 pesos.  To contact the reporter on this story:
